narratives.question_text:
What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
(Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments: Vector spaces, matrices, diagonalizability, etc.
I became more able to handle abstract mathematical concepts, learned how to write proofs, and a little bit of the linear algebra that is useful in other disciplines.
some basic knowledge of linear algebra
Improved proficiency at finding and understanding proofs, a new understanding of the foundations of linear algebra and how bigger ideas are built from previous ideas

This was my introduction to proof-writing (and it was tough! but so rewarding). I also learned what defines a field, vector space, linear transformation, kernel & image, dimension, subspace, matrix representation, linear independence, inner product, orthogonality, and diagonalization. The relationship between properties of linear transformation and matrices was a tough jump for me, but I learned a lot about it in this course. This was a really rewarding class! It took me a few weeks to get the hang of proof-writing, but I'm so glad I invested the time in doing so. I feel like I have a very good idea of why things are the way they are in linear algebra. I also enjoyed the final project that I wrote, which was an application of linear algebra to another field of interest.
very detailed concepts in linear algebra with a lot of proof-writing

It's still hard to put into words exactly what I learned in this course, but this was certainly a really good introduction to proof. I had done some linear algebra before, but I really enjoyed how in this course we actually learned the motives for developing certain concepts and operations (dot product, matrix multiplications, gaussian method, etc...). It just feels like I learned so much about Linear Algebra that although I know as a matter of fact I learned a lot, it's difficult to think back to what my understanding of Linear Algebra used to be.

We learned about traditional linear algebra concepts including vector spaces, linear transformations, etc. It is primarily a proof driven class, so we had an introduction to the concept, then had many propositions followed by proofs to those propositions. I feel a lot more comfortable taking more proof based classes in the future.
I developed my proof writing and gained insight on many things encountered in my previous math classes.

This course taught me the foundations of linear algebra and matrix theory, subjects I had never been exposed to before. In addition, my proof-writing and logical thinking skills developed greatly in this course.
Basics to Linear Algebra, matrices, proof-writing
Linear Algebra
Writing proofs, reasoning skills, complex linear algebra
Learned about how to write proofs and general linear algebra concepts.
I learned a lot about linear algebra from this course. But I learned all of it from Khan Academy or my friend who was a math major and offered to tutor me, and none from Or Landesberg.
I learned linear algebra.
Understanding matrices and using them as representations of linear transformations, solving linear equations, rudimentary how to write a proof.
I learned how to better write proofs and think critically

narratives.question_text:
What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
(Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments:
Strengths: The professor generally does a pretty good job explaining , although sometimes he can sound a little confusing. The psets are pretty interesting and helpful with understanding.
Weaknesses: I think the course was a bit rushed towards the end. The professor tried to get through too much material, so we ended up not having enough time to actually understand the materials before moving on. He also had to upload multiple addendums to better explain the material we could not get to in lecture, which sometimes made things more confusing. Also, it would be great if the professor can do a better job at explaining the purpose/goal of the material before we get into it. Sometimes it feels like I'm just copying down whatever theorem/proposition he puts down without knowing how it would lead to anything useful. (Also just a note, having the exam worth 40% was a bit concerning...)

The strength of this course is probably the support provided by the peer tutors. 

This course had many weaknesses. First, the course was poorly laid out throughout the semesterwe spent over half of the semester going over minutiae and then had to rush through 4 chapters of the book without much time to process. Second, the discussion sections were of little help, since it was difficult to follow the graduate student's train of thought. This is also usual with the main instructorthey both tended to overcomplicate things, and I believe it is why we didn't get to learn more practical and essential aspects of linear algebra. I feel that we were thrown with a thousand theorems and definitions disconnected from the broader picture in math, let alone in other subjects. Finally, the final exam was in a format very different from what we practiced throughout the semester, a situation that added unnecessary stress to a complicated semester. I don't understand what's the point of memorizing over 170 minor theorems and their proofs. Is memorizing helpful for understanding? No. Will students remember even 20% of those theorems one week after the exam? No.

Oh, I forgot. The feedback on our PSets after mid-semester stopped coming until a very short time before the final.
This course was quite confusing. I found that we rushed through a lot of things and didn't have proper motivation/justification for what we were doing.
Lectures were disorganized and hard to follow.

I thought the theory was solid, though I would have liked a little more on the application side (even though this is not 222) as we discussed not so many applications (could mention these applications in psets maybe)

The course does a great job of teaching linear algebra but I wish it was more explicit about teaching how to write proofs. Like, I still don't even know if I can write a 'proper' proofs or not because we never talked about what a proper proof was. I definitely fell like I've developed some intuition, but I honestly still feel iffy about proofs in general.

Strengths: there were a lot of resources in this course (office hours primarily) that made it difficult to "fail" this course and also some addendums on certain topics that filled in blanks. I found that doing proofs in class often inspired "aha!" moments which were really insightful. Also, I found the way that the professor explained concepts very clear. Whenever I struggled to recall a concept I'd written in my notes, I'd go back and watch the lecture to hear how he explained it. I liked how the professor tried his best to engage student suggestions and answers during a lecture too.
Weaknesses: this class felt a little depersonalized to me. I didn't feel like I had built a strong community among the students taking this course, other than appreciating the ULAs and instructors for all their work. For me, this is something I attribute mainly to COVID-era learning, but it made this course much harder. I also often struggled to actually do computational problems even though I understood the concepts, and I found that my TA session notes were often not very organized and helpful. Honestly, I think the second half of this course was tougher for me than the first half, and it felt like it went a little faster. My only other remark is that I sometimes felt that the professor assumed we knew more about notation/linear algebra than I actually did (I can't speak for others). My other classes used GradeScope and I would have preferred to have all my course submissions method be the same (I think GradeScope is often easier?) but the Ed Discussion was really well maintained. Overall, strengths outweigh weaknesses but this was a rewarding, albeit challenging course.
It is perfect in every way

I'd say that the strength of this course was its comprehensiveness, and how the course was very thorough in making sure that every claim lied upon axioms or previously established theorems. The homework was also very challenging, but at the same time rewarding.

Strengths: Or, the professor, is a new professor at Yale this year, but did a great job teaching the course. He and his lectures were very organized and I really liked the content that was taught. This was my first proof-based class, but I felt I picked it up fast. 
Weaknesses: The lectures were not too interactive, hence most kids watched the recorded lecture afterwards. I didn't mind this, but some students may prefer more breakout rooms, etc.
Mix: The problem sets were graded relatively easily so that helps your grade. They were not picky about the very specific parts of the proof and were more concerned with if you understood the overall logic. However on the midterm, the grading was very specific, which was something we were not expecting/prepared for, but Or curved it so it was okay.
This course was challenging but we got a lot of help, which was appreciated.

I think it was great that the professor would write the proofs in class and work through them instead of just talking about them. What would be very useful is if there was more time at the beginning of the class to really understand proofs and proof-writing since this is the first exposure for many people.

The lectures and problem sets provided excellent motivation for learning the concepts; the Psets in particular were well-cultivated and provided intellectual challenges that cemented my understanding. The exams, however, were a bit of an uneven experience: the first exam had a rather bizarre format of being a 32-hour take home exam and ended up yielding a remarkably low average; I do appreciate, though, that the instructor took this into account and curved the exam. The final was a totally different format, which made everyone very nervous, but it was actually much easier than the midterm (very much appreciated!) Overall, the exam experience wasn't too bad, I think I just would have liked more clarity in what our expectations should have been for each in terms of format and content. Finally, it felt like the pacing of the course was a bit off, as we ended up very rushed at the end, not being able to get more than a cursory glimpse of the last few concepts. Overall, though, I thought it was a great course!
Loved this course!!!!
The course was taught very well, I wish it had more applications though

The course does a good job at getting you used to writing proofs and thinking in a proof-oriented way. It could have been better at teaching how the proofs we learned applied to a more computational setting. In that sense, I would have liked a few more computational examples in class or as some supplemental material outside of confusing TA sessions.

Professor Landesberg spent the entirety of the class proving from definitions--he offered no geometric or conceptual explanations for topics that would have made them more intuitive. As a result, the class was not engaging and hard to follow.

This course was taxing beyond belief. The weakness of the course is the lack of help. The material is extremely hard, and our resources were very limited. Reading a textbook about math is not a proper addition to learning the material, as if you cannot understand it through a professor, reading about it will not help. Office hours were useless with TAs. Not because they were bad, but because students would simply hound them for their own needs, and so it was impossible for them to get to everyone's questions. Bottom line, more TAs were needed. Math 120 had multiple teachers and far more TAs in addition to Ximera. Unfortunately, this class only had one professor who was not amazing in regards to returning emails promptly and only two TAs. It was not enough for this type of course.

The strengths of this course include allowing students to drop their 2 lowest pset grades and allowing for late submission on 2 psets, and having the lectures recorded - mostly the structural things about the course. 

The weaknesses of the course center on how lectures are taught and the decisions made in how to communicate concepts. I did not find the teaching style of the professor to be particularly helpful - in particular, the lecture format involved little to no imagery and handwritten notes. Outside online resources taught me most of what I know conceptually, and helped me visualize and convince myself of things we only discussed abstractly in the course. Much of the teaching style was based on definitions and building upon those definitions to come to a conclusion in the proofs, but I can't say I understood the intuition behind the proofs. The class was a bit frustrating in this way. Especially if you are someone who has a surface level familiarity with mathematical notation, since that was a large part of proof writing and something lightly touched upon at the beginning of the course. I don't think the course had to be as confusing as it was, and highly recommend that if you take this course, to find a resource outside that you understand well.

In terms of learning how to write proofs, I think the course could do so much better. As someone who never took a proof writing course before, I did not have an idea of what a proof could look like, and what it would require. I think it would be helpful to future students for the instructor to spend time at the beginning of the course outlining what a proof is, and giving different examples of proofs. While I understand that much of learning how to write proofs comes by practicing, without an idea of what different forms proofs can take, practice isn't particularly useful, and there is an unnecessary amount of self teaching on the basics of proof writing that must occur.

Lastly, I'm not sure if this was just a result of the pandemic, but the response time for grading psets was very slow (at one point the past 4 psets hadn't been graded). That is something that could be improved.

I think there could have been more one on one instruction between teacher and student, and the psets could have corresponded more to the tests. I thought the professor was very friendly and open to questions, but I do think that grading policies could have been more clear throughout.

narratives.question_text: Among the practices in this course geared toward learning during the COVID-19 pandemic, which succeeded and which could be improved? Please comment on course practices that allowed for virtual engagement. (Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments: No mechanisms for engaging students virtually were implemented. In particular, no detailed syllabus for the semester was provided. With a detailed syllabus, I am referring to a description of topics to be covered per class. Thus, it was just a matter of going to class and hearing what was being taughtno chances of actually reading the material beforehand to have a grasp of what's being covered in lecture. I would strongly recommend that the instructors of this course (or its equivalent) in the future provide a detailed syllabus so that students get a chance to improve their learning.
With notes that perfect, it doesn't matter if its over zoom or not.

I wish the lectures could have had subtitles for recordings. I'm not sure if there's an automatic setting for that on Zoom recordings, but a lot of my other classes had it and it made it easier for me--a visual learner--to grasp things a little faster. I do like how there were two sections of the lecture and the professor tried his best to engage students by asking questions or asking for suggestions. I also wish TA session notes could be posted because that would have increased accessibility. Overall though, this class did exceed my expectations for a lecture class during a pandemic.
Everything was great

Success: We had a take home midterm where we had 32 hours to submit. The proofs were more challenging than the ones we were doing on psets, but the extra time made it fair. 
Improvements: Nothing too much.
The live virtual lectures were successful because there were not too many students so you could always ask questions.
The recorded lectures, recorded TA sessions, and various office hours times made it a very accessible course for students no matter where in the world they were taking it from.
The workshops and lectures were engaging.
I think the recorded lectures were good. The TA sessions were far too long to be able to pay attention for the whole time over zoom.
There was no virtual engagement. We would be lectured for an hour and a half and most were too scared to ask questions as the class had a feeling of competitiveness to it.
lectures worked fairly well, but the TA sessions could have been much better organized
The live lectures were successful, and it was really helpful that the lectures were recorded and the lecture notes were posted to Canvas.

narratives.question_text:
Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
(Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments: Well if want to take a challenging proof-based math course... do it. But if you are not a fan of math, maybe try something else. This course is great but you will be tearing your hair out at some point, so do it only if you enjoy that.

I wouldn't recommend this course. There's too much discussion (and wasted time) over small details which are eventually unimportant to anyone who is not interested in being a Math major. Save yourself some headaches and take 222 (or whatever course will replace it). I would much rather memorize techniques that will be useful somewhere else than an abundance of theorems. I can practice problem-solving techniques, but I can't practice doing proofs.

This course is terrible. If you are choosing between 222 and 225 take 222. There is no introduction on how to write proofs they just go straight into them. The course is super hard to follow and I ended up just not going to class anymore because I felt like I wasn't learning anything. Paid Yale tuition to teach myself linear algebra from the textbook. The test were ridiculous and so different, went from a 36 hour take home  open note test to a closed everything proctored final exam.
Yes, a great course to take even if you are not a math major and don't have prior proof experience.

Yes, it will likely be your first proof based course. The content of the class can be a bit confusing at times since linear algebra is totally different from calculus or algebra, but linear algebra is a common and popular course so doing the bare minimum outside research into a confusing topic will probably clear things up fats. Indeed, most of the difficulty will just come from learning to write proofs.  Honestly, they kinda just throw you into the deep end in regards to this (I don't think we really ever discussed how to write proofs in class) but p-set will be graded leniently and your the lowest 2 were dropped so you have time and leeway to gain intuition for proofs just from doing the p-sets, going to office hours, and watching your professors do proofs. I really enjoyed this course because it was the first time in a while that I felt like I was learning stuff that was purely 'new' in a math class. I imagine that this course if quite professor dependent so if you have the option I recommend Or Landesberg, his class was very clearly organized and his enthusiasm for the content is contagious.

Yeah, take it! I'd primarily recommend this class to anyone looking to develop their mental framework for problem-solving, since learning how to write proofs will do just that. This class is manageable with a 5 credit course load, but you should start problem sets before the peer tutor/ULAs hold office hours. I found that doing psets during office hours made the time go by a lot faster, and I could receive help if I needed it. I also would recommend this course to someone who wants to learn about why linear algebra works the way it does. I personally didn't shop 222 since I'd heard that if you want to take further math classes, 225 builds a stronger proof-based framework. I don't regret taking this course! Just make sure to keep up to date with lectures and homework or else the work accumulates VERY quickly. The textbook is also super helpful, and the professor is happy to re-explain or elaborate on any concepts during his office hours or via Ed!
Definitely, please take it with Or since he is amazing at teaching, one of a kind class, very clear notes and explanation of deeply sophisticated concepts in linear algebra

Yes! I think that this course is a must for anyone that's thinking of majoring in anything like math or stats or of that nature. I was also on the fence between Math 222 and 225 at the beginning of the course; looking back, math 225 was defintely more work, but I also do not regret my decision; so many things learned!

Yes! The content of this course was very interesting. it was my first proof based class, but it didn't take long to pick up. Or, the professor, is very organized and the class is well structured. The work load wasn't too much, we had weekly psets, one midterm, one final, and one optional project.
I would recommend this course to any students wanting to expand their math knowledge.

Yes, I absolutely would. Any student who is looking to take more math courses in the future and wants to build their understanding of linear algebra in a logical, proof-based, rigorous way should take this class. However if you want to focus on applications instead of theory, you should definitely take 222 instead.
A great course! If you are trying to decide between 222 and 225, definitely pick this one, especially if it's taught by prof. Landesberg.
Yes!!
Yes, loved the experience. Very interesting course to learn proofs and linear algebra - a domain that has applications across the board.

I would if you are interested in taking a proof-based mathematics class. It gets you used to that style of math. Psets can be time consuming but are very doable if you are willing to devote time to them and ask questions. It is definitely not for everyone though.
Not for non math majors
No.

No. The only way I would recommend this course is if a student had to take it for a major. Otherwise, avoid this course. the workload is tremendous, the material is extremely difficult, and you really feel like you are on an island to figure things out.
Only if you have the extra time to teach yourself things.
If you have to take it, take it. I think it teaches necessary proof writing skills, but it can be frustrating at times
Yes, if you want to learn the theory behind linear algebra and build up to thoroughly understanding the applications.
